[h1]Constants[/h1]

[b]Constants[/b] are similar to variables except that they cannot be changed or undefined after they've been defined.
Begin the name of your constant with a letter or an underscore.
To create a constant, use the [b]define()[/b] function: [code format="raw" ][b]define[/b](name, value, case-insensitive)[/code]
Parameters:
[b]name[/b]: Specifies the name of the constant;
[b]value[/b]: Specifies the value of the constant;
[b]case-insensitive[/b]: Specifies whether the constant name should be case-insensitive. Default is [b]false;[/b]

The example below creates a constant with a [b]case-sensitive[/b] name: [code format="php" codeId="463"]<?php
  define("MSG", "Hi SoloLearners!");
  echo MSG;

   // Outputs "Hi SoloLearners!"
?> [/code]
The example below creates a constant with a [b]case-insensitive[/b] name: [code format="php" codeId="464"]<?php
  define("MSG", " Hi SoloLearners!", [b]true[/b]);
  echo msg;

  // Outputs "Hi SoloLearners!"
?>[/code]
[note]No dollar sign ($) is necessary before the constant name.[/note]
